<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="440" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1461,1704]" pageId="9" pageNumber="440">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1461,1487]" pageId="9" pageNumber="440">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is close to 
<taxonomicName authority="Kamiya" authorityName="Kamiya" authorityYear="1963" box="[539,771,1461,1488]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Axinoscymnus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="440" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="beneficus">
<emphasis box="[539,676,1461,1488]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="440">A. beneficus</emphasis>
Kamiya
</taxonomicName>
in male genitalia but can be distinguished from the latter by the elytral pattern and the blunt tip of penis according to the illustrations given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Poorani, J. &amp; Booth, R. G." box="[1073,1349,1497,1523]" pageId="9" pageNumber="440" pagination="56 - 68" refId="ref16643" refString="Poorani, J. &amp; Booth, R. G. (2021) Nomenclatural notes on three species of Scymnini (Coleoptera: Coccinellidae) from Ceylon. Oriental Insects, 55 (1), 56 - 68. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00305316.2020.1748134" type="journal article" year="2021">Poorani &amp; Booth (2021)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
